r the creation of a new identity for French military and civilian settlers.Effros uses France's violent colonial war, its efforts to document the ancient Roman past, and its brutal treatment of the region's Arab and Berber inhabitants to underline the close entanglement of knowledge production with European imperialism. Significantly, Incidental Archaeologists shows how the French experience in Algeria contributed to the professionalization of archaeology in metropolitan France.Effros demonstrates how the archaeological expeditions undertaken by the French in Algeria and the documentation they collected of ancient Roman military accomplishments reflected French confidence that they would learn from Rome's technological accomplishments and succeed, where the Romans had failed, in mastering the region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aArchaeology and statezFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aArchaeologyxPolitical aspectszAlgeriaxHistoryy19th century. 0aArchaeologyxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistoryy19th century. 4aArchaeology. 4aEurope. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2018z978311066747908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishz978311060403008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018z9783110603149oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501718540423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501718540.jpg  a978-3-11-060403-0  EBOOK 